alternatives.transcript: so leslie my patient is leslie palmer who's a sixty two year old female whose chief complaint is shortness of breath and fatigue the patient's shortness of breath began about two months ago and has been getting worse patient describes feeling fluttering in her chest and like she's going to pass out three days ago the patient presented to her primary care physician where they ordered tests and her primary care physician then recommended for her to go to the emergency room patient states that her symptoms get worse with activity and are better at rest patient is currently sleeping in a recliner at night because laying down makes her symptoms worse on a scale of zero to ten patient describes the severity of her discomfort as a seven or an eight as far as her social history goes patient has a balanced diet and walks every day prior to experiencing symptoms she drinks a cup of cup of coffee every day and is an elementary school teacher who lives with her husband as far as her past medical history goes she was diagnosed with hypertension fifteen years ago and pulmonary sarcoidosis twenty five years ago she is up to date on immunizations and has no hospitalizations and no allergies as far as surgery goes she had a cardiac catheter one year ago and that was found to have no obstructive coronary artery disease present for her medication she's currently on lisinopril ten milligrams once a day for hypertension and then her prednisone ten milligrams once a day for pulmonary sarcoidosis patient states that she's compliant with these medications and began the lisinopril fifteen years ago and the prednisone twenty five years ago as far as her family history goes patient's mother passed away at the age of forty due to sudden death and her father passed at age fifty nine due to a myocardial infarction as far as pertinent review of system goes patient has experienced fatigue weight gain of eight pounds over two weeks swelling in lower extremities near syncope palpations wheezing dyspnea with exertion and orthopenia as far as pertinent physical exam patient has a positive jugular venous detention and no carotid roots they should have a positive systolic murmur with s four and a positive gallop as far as when listening to her lungs i heard by basilar rails and wheezing looking at her lower extremity she did have a edema in her lower extremities as well as a normal dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial pulse she also does not have any epigastric roots and no pulsatile masses as far as her abnormal vitals go she had a heart rate of one hundred and ten a respiratory rate of twenty an oxygen saturation of ninety one percent and a blood pressure of one thirty six over ninety nine for her results of her lab and imaging her lab work shows that she has an elevated pmp of four thousand her chest x-ray shows cardiomegaly mediastinal fullness as well as pulmonary edema her echo shows restrictive cardiomyopathy with increased wall thickness and an ejection fraction of fifty five percent her ekg shows normal sinus rhythm and normal access nonsustained ventricular and nonsustained ventricular tachycardia my leading differential diagnosis is sarcoidosis restrictive cardiomyopathy with a new york heart association's rate rating of three as far as the car cause goes i explained the patient that most likely this is due to the pulmonary sarcoidosis that went to her heart and resulted in arrhythmia and congestive heart failure as far as assessment and plan goes i am admitting the patient to telemetry sorry condition is serious allergies none vitals every two hours she can be out of bed with assistance as far as nursing interventions go this would include strict io daily weight dvt prophylaxis o two via nasal cannula as well as maintaining oxygen saturation greater than ninety six percent a diet of low sodium is also recommended as well as for iv fluids a saline lock and keeping the vein open as far as medications go i recommend continuing lisinopril ten milligrams once daily administering in deodorant a hundred and fifty milligram iv increasing prednisone to sixty milligrams once daily and adding furosemide forty milligram iv diagnostic labs slash imaging would be cmp labs as far as specialists and consults i recommended interventional cardiologists who discuss the possibility of an automatic implantable cardiac defibrillator as well as nuclear medicine and radiologists to discuss an fdg pet scan as far as lifestyle modifications i recommended to her focusing on a healthy diet weight reduction and physical activity when she's cleared by the physician the patient had no further questions and i went ahead and let her know that her husband could come up and i would explain the information to him thank you
